A better pattern in test code would be:
@Before
public void setup() {
    this.mutationQueue = new MutationQueue(...);
    this.outbox = new MutationOutbox(..., mutationQueue, ...);
}

@Test
public void someTest() {
    // Access the queue directly instead of exposing a getter on the outbox
    mutationQueue.doSomething();
}

but it requires us to update the constructor which is a breaking change to all its consumers. It also make all its consumer import the MutationQueue class hence couple with it, which those consumers may not even care about.

